content.description:
Start with a high heel or smearing. Awkwardly maneuver your way in between the shelves and reach up for the obvious ledge. Grab the juggy pocket to the left of the ledge and top out.

 For an easier and less uncomfortable problem, start higher and just reach directly for the ledge.
content.location: (Holds shown clearly in photo). Start with left hand in good hueco and right hand in shallow hueco.

content.description: Start on the same holds as “Daily Vitamin D Dose” move left hand up the obvious  pocket, right hand to the sloper, find your feet and match the sloper. Left hand move to a good pocket right hand to the smaller higher  pocket find the left foot and mantle top out.
content.location: Back wall holds are pretty obvious and wall was recently cleaned

content.description: Depending on your height, begin with a mantle into a big reach and match the obvious slopey crimp if you're tall or potentially reach directly up with right hand in a decent undercling if you're shorter. Then grab one of the two upper pockets and top out.
content.location:
Look for the two identical looking pockets near the top out ledge about 2 feet apart, the climb is directly below.

 Start can vary depending on person, but one hand should start on the surprisingly deep undercling marked in photo with a circle.

 Taller people will likely want to put their right hand on the big ledge marked with an X and do a mantle and shorter people may want to use a slightly higher up jug with their foot on the X.

content.description:
This problem is basically just one hard mantle move, or maybe heelhook. It is possible that if you clean enough dirt away you might be able to find other holds.

 If you climb farther from the same starting holds and top out over there it could be considered a different problem.
content.location: Starting holds are the obvious jugs on the lower shelf, there are a few but it doesn't really matter much since the first move getting to the ledge is very easy.

content.description:
Start in an awkward position and then lean back enough to grab a crimp on the underside of the lip and use it to reach all the way to the top of the wall. 

 Somewhat height dependant but I think there are good options for most people.
content.location:
Middle of the wall. Look for the bulge in the top out shelf and this climb is directly beneath.

 Starting holds marked in photo. Left hand starts in juggy semi-hidden Mono/ledge (better than it sounds) and right hand pressed onto a slopey section above some blue graffiti with a high left foot. (Sort of a mantle position).

content.description:
Probably the most obvious line on the wall. Fun movement and clear holds, not too awkward. Use the big pocket in the middle of the ledge and go left to top out on the same ledge as Supercharged Collagen.

 Toping out directly above may be possible if a lot of dirt is cleaned away, and may create a harder variation of the climb.
content.location: Start with left hand in one of the pockets directly beneath the ledge pocket and right in juggy pocket at the same height. (Shown clearly in photo)

content.description:
20 ft tall wall with lots of soil and debris along the middle ledges. Usually in shade. All top outs end in the middle about 10 feet up, very good flat landings for the entire wall. Fence at the very top of the wall.

 This area seems to have been overlooked for a long time due to it being dirty and the climbing being short and awkward, but a few fun bits of movement and some interesting beta can be found.
